{
  "query": "How do long-term and temporary fishery closures compare in their effects on marine fish abundance?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the examined studies, temporary and long-term fishery closures show different patterns in their effects on marine fish abundance. For temporary fishery closures, Action 2664 reported that one before-and-after, site comparison study in the Atlantic Ocean found no increase in the biomass of the spawning stock of cod following a temporary fishery closure compared to fished areas over nine years, and no change in cod catches over nine years compared to fished areas. However, the same study found that during temporary closures, catch rates of red mullet and total catch (fish and invertebrates combined) increased after temporary closures compared to before, though European hake did not show this increase. For long-term fishery closures, Action 2655 reported that two site comparison studies found higher abundance of only one of seven fish species in areas closed to groundfish fisheries for six to eight years compared to open areas, but lower abundance of monkfish. One study found that lesser sandeel biomass and density peaked but there was no overall increase in the three years after a long-term fishery closure. Another study found more young salmon and similar numbers of older salmon returning to rivers in the five years after long-term closure of a commercial coastal fishery. Action 2680 reported that a global review found 10 of 11 studies showing effects of protection from restricting fishing activity in marine reserves found higher abundance of fish inside the areas compared to areas without fishing restrictions.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2664",
    "2655",
    "2680"
  ]
}

