{
  "query": "Besides changing hook type in longline fisheries, what other gear modifications can reduce unwanted catches of sharks and rays?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several gear modifications for longline fisheries can reduce unwanted catches of sharks and rays besides changing hook type. Modifying longline configuration by increasing the lead weight on mid-water longlines to increase the sinking rate reduced catches of unwanted sharks and/or rays compared to standard longlines (Action 2699). Using nylon instead of wire hook attachments also reduced unwanted shark and/or ray catches, although one study found that survival of unwanted sharks caught on tuna longlines was reduced with nylon hook lines compared to wire (Action 2699). Attaching electropositive deterrent materials to longlines caught fewer unwanted sharks and rays compared to standard fishing gear or gears with non-deterrent materials, though results were mixed across studies with some finding similar catches compared to gear with no deterrents (Action 2696). Using different bait types showed mixed results, with two systematic global reviews finding that using different bait types did not affect the number of unwanted sharks and rays caught (Action 2700). Using artificial light on fishing gear was examined in only one study on shrimp trawl nets, which found fewer unwanted fish catches when lights were fitted to the fishing line compared to conventional trawl, though this was not specifically tested on longlines for sharks and rays (Action 2695).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2699",
    "2696",
    "2700",
    "2695"
  ]
}

