{
  "query": "What are the comparative effects on fish abundance of prohibiting all static fishing gear versus prohibiting only line fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, there are limited direct comparative studies between prohibiting all static fishing gear versus prohibiting only line fishing. \n\nFor prohibiting all static fishing gear: One study in the Coral Sea (Australia) found that in areas closed to non-towed fishing gears, overall shark abundance was higher when sampled with longlines but not gillnets compared to areas where commercial gillnets were permitted (Action 2670). Additionally, shark length was greater for two of five species/groups in closed areas compared to areas where commercial gillnets were permitted (Action 2670).\n\nFor prohibiting only line fishing: One study in the Indian Ocean (South Africa) found that prohibiting offshore line fishing and all other boat-based fishing in a marine protected area zone resulted in higher abundances of four of four fish species over-exploited by line fishing, compared to zones where boat-based line and spear fishing was permitted (Action 2671). The same study found that four of four fish species over-exploited by line fishing were larger in the closed zone after two to seven years (Action 2671).\n\nFor broader bottom fishing gear restrictions (including both mobile and static gears): Studies showed mixed results - one study found higher numbers of larger and older cod in areas where fishing gears targeting bottom-dwelling species had been prohibited for 15 years, while another found no effect on fish densities after 2-7 years of protection, and a third found that fish densities varied between species/groups and were affected by depth and temperature (Action 2654).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2670",
    "2671",
    "2654"
  ]
}

