{
  "query": "What are the outcomes for fish populations when marine protected areas are managed with zonation systems that permit some fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Marine protected areas with zonation systems that permit some fishing show variable but generally positive outcomes for fish populations compared to unprotected areas. Action 2674 found that fish species richness was higher in no-fishing zones compared to partially fished zones and unprotected areas after 10-15 years. For fish condition, larger average lengths were observed for multiple fish species in no-take zones compared to partially fished zones after 3 years, and fish sizes were largest within no-take zones compared to partially fished zones. Fish abundance outcomes varied with the level of restriction, with non-fished zones showing higher density, biomass, and abundance compared to fished zones inside protected areas after 10-27 years, though effects varied between fish feeding groups and zone protection levels. Tagged fish remained mainly in zones where all or nearly all fishing was prohibited over 4-9 year periods. Action 2680 reported that global reviews found 10 of 11 studies showed higher fish abundance inside areas with fishing restrictions compared to areas without restrictions, and fish survival was higher in marine parks with low fishing intensity compared to more intensively fished areas outside. Fish inside restricted areas reached larger average sizes and older ages compared to more intensively fished areas. Action 2679 found that areas fished only periodically had greater fish biomass than openly fished areas and similar biomass to permanently closed areas after 6 years, with higher fish catch rates than openly fished areas.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2674",
    "2680",
    "2679"
  ]
}

