{
  "query": "How does the effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gear vary between the North Atlantic and other regions like the Mediterranean or Indian Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from marine conservation studies, the effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gear shows varied outcomes across the North Atlantic, Mediterranean, and Indian Ocean regions. In the North Atlantic Ocean (Canada, Portugal), studies found mixed results - one study showed higher total fish biomass after 15 years of prohibition, while another found no effect on bottom-dwelling fish abundance after 10 years of closure. Additionally, a North Atlantic study found no increase in young haddock recruitment or survival seven years after closure (Action 2673).\n\nIn the Mediterranean Sea, effectiveness varied by species and timeframe. Studies found higher biomass of adult red mullet after 14 years and increased recruitment of young red mullet after closure to bottom-towed fishing gears. However, the effect on fish size varied between individual fish groups (Action 2673). For invertebrates in the Mediterranean, areas prohibiting bottom trawling for 15-20 years showed different overall invertebrate community composition compared to trawled areas, with some studies finding higher invertebrate diversity after 15 years while others found no differences after 20 years (Action 2099).\n\nIn the Indian Ocean (Tasmania, Kenya), studies showed increased abundances of long-snouted seahorses after one year of mobile bottom gear prohibition, but no effect on short-snouted seahorses. Overall fish catch rates were higher in areas prohibiting beach and all seine nets for 3-6 years, though effects varied between individual fish groups. In some Indian Ocean locations, fish size effects varied between fish groups and habitat types (Action 2673).\n\nCross-regional studies examining marine protected areas with fishing prohibitions found that 15 studies in the Indian Ocean, 12 in the Mediterranean Sea, and 7 in the Atlantic Ocean showed that protected areas generally had higher fish abundances and larger fish sizes compared to fished areas, though effectiveness varied between species, depths, and habitat types (Action 2682).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2673",
    "2099",
    "2682"
  ]
}

