{
  "query": "How do separator trawls and topless trawls compare in their effectiveness at reducing unwanted fish catch?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on available studies, both separator trawls and topless trawls show effectiveness in reducing unwanted fish catch, but they have been evaluated in different contexts and with varying degrees of success. Separator trawls have been examined in two studies and showed positive results for reducing unwanted catch in both cases. In the North Sea, a separator trawl separated unwanted cod from target fish species into the lower codend, where a larger mesh size allowed more unwanted smaller cod to escape capture (Action 2711). In the Atlantic Ocean, a separator trawl fitted with a square-mesh escape panel caught less of one of two unwanted fish species in a crustacean fishery (Action 2711). Topless trawls have been more extensively studied with four studies examining their effectiveness. Two of the four studies found that topless trawls reduced the catch of unwanted Atlantic cod and discards of commercial fish species compared to conventional trawl types (Action 2712). One study found that topless trawls reduced unwanted catches of larger but not smaller haddock and larger Atlantic cod only in one of two cases, compared to standard trawl types (Action 2712). Another study found that discarded catches of one of four commercial fish species were reduced in topless trawls (Action 2712). The studies for topless trawls were conducted in the North Sea, Gulf of Maine, Skagerrak and Baltic Sea regions (Action 2712).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2711",
    "2712"
  ]
}

