{
  "query": "What is the evidence for using electropositive deterrents on fishing gear to reduce unwanted catches of sharks and rays?",
  "relevant_summary": "Nine studies examined the effect of attaching electropositive deterrents to fishing gear on marine fish populations, conducted in the Atlantic Ocean (USA, Canada, Bahamas), Gulf of Alaska (USA), South Pacific Ocean (Australia), Tasman Sea (Australia), with one global systematic review and two laboratory studies (USA) (Action 2696). For behavior change, three of four replicated studies found that electropositive deterrent materials attached near bait reduced feeding attempts and bait consumption of spiny dogfish, great hammerhead and draughtboard sharks compared to gear without deterrents, while one study found no reduction in bait consumption by bonnethead and young lemon sharks (Action 2696). For unwanted catch reduction, two of four replicated, controlled studies in the Gulf of Alaska, Pacific Ocean and Atlantic Ocean found that fishing gear (longlines and traps) fitted with electropositive deterrent materials caught fewer unwanted spiny dogfish, longnose skate, sharks and rays, and fewer undersized halibut compared to standard fishing gear or gear with non-deterrent materials (Action 2696). However, two other studies and a global systematic review found that electropositive deterrents resulted in similar catches of unwanted spiny dogfish, sharks (total catch), blue shark and sharks and rays (total catch) compared to gear with no deterrents (Action 2696).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2696"
  ]
}

