{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of ceasing all fishing in a marine protected area on fish community composition and species richness?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence from multiple studies, ceasing all fishing in marine protected areas demonstrates several benefits for fish community composition and species richness. Seven site comparison studies found that protected areas where all fishing had been prohibited for between three and 16 years had a different fish community composition compared to fished areas (Action 2682). For species richness, fourteen of 20 site comparison studies found that marine protected areas that had prohibited all fishing for between one to more than 25 years had higher fish species richness compared to fished areas, though six studies found similar fish species richness between one and 20 years after all fishing was banned (Action 2682). One systematic review found no difference in species richness between unfished protected areas and fished areas, and effects varied with sampling method used in some cases (Action 2682). However, one study found lower total fish species richness in marine protected areas closed to all fishing with limited exceptions for up to seven years compared to unprotected areas (Action 2681). The effects on fish abundance were predominantly positive, with thirty of 54 site comparison studies finding that marine protected areas prohibiting all fishing for up to 25 years or more had higher abundances of all fish, fishery targeted fish species, non-fishery targeted fish species, and most individual fish species monitored compared to unprotected fished areas (Action 2682). The benefits extended beyond abundance to include larger fish sizes overall and larger individuals of most fish species monitored after one to 22 years of protection (Action 2682).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2682",
    "2681"
  ]
}

