{
  "query": "How does using a square mesh codend compare to rotating a diamond mesh codend for improving size-selectivity in trawl nets?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both square mesh codends and rotating diamond mesh codends have been studied for improving size-selectivity in trawl nets, with varying effectiveness depending on fish species and body shape. For square mesh codends, 14 studies found that 6 showed improved size selectivity for species including silver hake, horse mackerel, European hake, axillary seabream, poor cod, greater forkbeard, blue whiting, discarded fish and three of four commercially targeted fish compared to diamond mesh codends (Action 2714). However, 5 studies found no difference in size selectivity between square and diamond mesh codends for Atlantic mackerel, long rough dab, yellowtail scad and striped seapike, rockfish and flatfish, and three of four commercially important bottom fish species (Action 2714). The effectiveness varied with fish body shape, with three of three and five of five roundfish species showing improved size selectivity, but not for one flatfish species (Action 2714). For rotating diamond mesh codends, 6 studies found that 4 of 5 studies showed that turning the orientation of diamond mesh in trawl codends by 90\u00b0 resulted in better size selection of cod, red mullet and common pandora, and round-bodied fish species, but not of plaice, annular sea bream, and flatfish species, compared to standard orientation diamond mesh codends (Action 2715). One study found that turned mesh did not improve the size selectivity of cod, plaice and flounder (Action 2715). Square mesh codends also showed additional benefits beyond selectivity, with 10 of 16 studies finding reduced unwanted catches of non-target or non-marketable fish compared to diamond mesh codends (Action 2714).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2714",
    "2715",
    "2724"
  ]
}

