{
  "query": "How do the effects on fish community composition of prohibiting all commercial fishing compare between the Tasman Sea and the South Atlantic Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, the effects on fish community composition of prohibiting all commercial fishing differ between the Tasman Sea and South Atlantic Ocean. In the Tasman Sea, two before-and-after studies found that fish assemblage/species composition was different before and after prohibiting all commercial fishing, specifically in an estuary after two years and in the nearby wider region surrounding two marine reserves five years after their creation (Action 2667). In contrast, in the South Atlantic Ocean, one site comparison study found no change in species composition between a reserve closed to all commercial fishing for 40 years and unprotected fished areas (Action 2667). Regarding species richness and diversity, the South Atlantic Ocean study found no difference in overall fish diversity between a protected area closed to all commercial fishing for 40 years compared to unprotected fished areas (Action 2667). In the Tasman Sea, one study found that most fish species in an estuary in a marine reserve had a lower abundance two years after it was closed to all commercial fishing than before, as did one of two reference sites in unprotected adjacent estuaries (Action 2667). The studies indicate that while the Tasman Sea showed changes in community composition following commercial fishing prohibitions, the South Atlantic Ocean showed no detectable changes in species composition even after 40 years of protection.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2667"
  ]
}

