{
  "query": "What are the comparative effects of long-term versus temporary fishery closures on marine fish populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from studies examining fishery closures, there are distinct differences between the effects of temporary and long-term closures on marine fish populations.\n\nTemporary fishery closures showed limited and mixed effects on fish populations. Studies found no increase in spawning stock biomass of cod, no change in survival or length composition of cod, and no change in cod catches over nine years following temporary closures (Action 2664). However, some benefits were observed in specific contexts - catch rates of red mullet and total catch increased after temporary closures over 10 years, and spear fisher catch numbers of herbivorous fish increased during temporary grouper fishery closures (Action 2664). Tagged adult cod spent nearly a third of their time inside seasonally closed spawning areas, providing some protection during spawning periods (Action 2664).\n\nLong-term fishery closures demonstrated more substantial and consistent benefits for fish populations. Studies found higher abundance of some fish species in areas closed to groundfish fisheries for six to eight years, increased numbers of young salmon returning to rivers after five years of coastal fishery closure, and improved condition with higher weights of young salmon (Action 2655). However, effects varied by species - only one of seven fish species showed higher abundance, and monkfish had lower abundance in closed areas (Action 2655). Long-term closures also reduced fishing effort and unwanted catch of cod compared to before closure (Action 2655).\n\nMarine protected areas with complete fishing prohibitions for extended periods (1-25+ years) showed the most comprehensive benefits. These areas had higher fish abundances, larger fish sizes, higher species richness and diversity, different community composition, increased reproductive success, and provided protection for commercially important species compared to fished areas (Action 2682). The effects strengthened with longer protection periods and varied between species based on their commercial target status and food chain position (Action 2682).\n\nPeriodic fishing regimes showed intermediate effects, with protected areas fished only for short periods having greater biomass than openly fished areas and similar biomass to permanently closed areas after 18 months to six years (Action 2679).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2664",
    "2655",
    "2679",
    "2682"
  ]
}

